      List<Date> getAllEffectiveDates()
      Returns a sorted list of distinct effective and expiration dates that exist on EffDated beans in the branch.

      Looking at every effective and expiration date of every bean in the branch to build this list is expensive. Call this once then cache the result if you know that the beans won't change while you use this information.

      An EffDatedKey only really applies to EffDateds as an EffDatedBranch is the same throughout its effective range (or its period range) so there is no difference between the "logical" bean and the actual bean.

    • getPeriodId

      Key getPeriodId()
      Every branch belongs to a period, identified by its PeriodId. When a new submission or renewal is created the new branch is assigned a new PeriodId. When a new branch is created in the same period as another branch (e.g. a policy change) it shares the "based on" or "original" branch's PeriodId. A period often has several branches associated with it, both promoted and in draft, but will have only one "most recent" or "in-force" branch associated with it. This in-force branch is the most recently promoted branch associated with a period. The other promoted branches represent earlier versions of the in-force branch in model-time. Often when we refer to the "period" we're actually referring to the most recently bound branch in a period, ignoring the other, "older" branches that are also associated with the period.

      To find all the branches associated with a period find all branches with the same PeriodId.

      Returns:
      Period Id of this branch.

    • getPublicID

      String getPublicID()
      The external ID for this entity.

      PublicID values are automatically created during the commit, if not previously set. The format is random, meeting security requirements based on current industry standards. For example:

      • pc:SYinDB2XTOgNZFs1NpxU8
      • pc:Sf8QS4N5RBS-h8_pj-Oy_
      • pc:SBwBzylneecSNr6_Ub4IO
      Your configuration code must not assume any particular format for PublicID values, in either the prefix or body portion of the string, or even assume the existence of a prefix. Do not make any assumptions at all about the content of a PublicID value, including expectations that values are sequential, numeric, or prefixed.

      You can subclass and override AbstractBundleTransactionCallback.afterSetIds(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle) if you need to see the value in the same commit. 

      
  var note = new Note(bundle)
  bundle.addBundleTransactionCallback(new AbstractBundleTransactionCallback() {
     override function afterSetIds(b : Bundle) {
       log.info("Created Note " + note.PublicID)
     }
  })

    • getSliceDate

      Date getSliceDate()
      Date which this bean is "sliced" or viewed. If you traverse from this bean to another bean or beans via a link or array, only beans that are effective at this slice date will be returned. The beans that are returned will be sliced at this date as well. If NULL then the bean is in "window" mode.

      In most cases a bean will be sliced, window mode is used in special cases.

      Specified by:
      getSliceDate in interface EffDatedBase
      Returns:
      Date which bean is sliced or null if in window mode.

    • getSliceUntyped

      EffDatedBase getSliceUntyped(Date sliceDate)
      Slice this bean at a particular date. This bean can be unsliced or sliced when this method is called. The slice date must be within the effective range of this bean or an exception will be thrown. If you want to get at the version of this "logical" bean at a date outside of this particular bean's effective range then use this.getVersionListUntyped().getVersionAsOf(sliceDate).getSliceUntyped(sliceDate).

    • getVersionListUntyped

      EffDatedVersionList getVersionListUntyped()
      Get the version list for this bean. An EffDatedVersionList is a representation of a logical bean through its effective range. For example, if a bean has changes at three separate effective dates then the version list will comprise 3 versions of the bean, one for each of these dates.

      You can use an EffDatedVersionList to traverse from this bean to other linked beans in window mode. Recall that in window mode you cannot traverse links directly from the bean.

      Although an EffDatedBranch only has a single version throughout its effective range you can still get its EffDatedVersionList in order to navigate in window mode from the branch to its related EffDateds.

      Specified by:
      getVersionListUntyped in interface EffDatedBase
      Returns:
      Version list for this bean

    • isPromoted

      boolean isPromoted()
      Check if this bean or branch has been promoted. A promoted bean is also locked and cannot be changed.

      An EffDated is never promoted independent of its related EffDatedBranch, meaning if the branch is promoted every bean in the graph will be promoted, and if the branch is not promoted no bean in the graph can be promoted.

      Specified by:
      isPromoted in interface EffDatedBase
      Returns:
      True if promoted.

    • isResolveWithFuturePeriods

      boolean isResolveWithFuturePeriods()
      When a branch is promoted and there exists a future bound period (or periods, but multiple would be rare) then this method returns true until it is cleared.

      This value can then be checked later to see if you want to apply the changes on this branch to that future period. Once it's cleared you will no longer have that option.

      Returns:
      True if when promoted there exited a future bound period.

      boolean isSlice()
      Whether this bean is sliced. If a bean is sliced then you can navigate from this bean to another bean or beans via a link or array, if it's unsliced (in "window" mode) you cannot navigate from this bean.

      In most cases a bean will be sliced, window mode is used in special cases.

    • lockBranch

      void lockBranch()
      Prevents further changes from occurring on this branch or any beans within this branch's graph. A branch is always locked before it's promoted, but there are cases where a branch will be locked but not promoted. For example, a declined submission is locked but not promoted.

      There are some internal fields that can be changed on a locked branch but otherwise it's immutable.

    • refresh

      KeyableBean refresh()
      Refreshes this bean with the latest database version.

      This method does nothing if the bean is edited or inserted in its current bundle. If the bean no longer exists in the database, then null is returned. If the bean has been evicted from its bundle, then null is returned. Otherwise, this bean is returned, with its contents updated.

      void remove()
      Marks this bean for remove. A bean marked for remove will be deleted or retired when the transaction is committed. Once a bean is marked for remove, it cannot be switched to update, edit, or read.

      WARNING: This method is designed for simple custom entities which are normally not associated with other entities. Undesirable results may occur when used on out-of-box entities.

    • touch

      void touch()
      Set's the version of the bean to the next value (i.e. the bean version original value+1) Multiple calls to this method on the same bean will result in the same value being used for the version (i.e. it is idempotent). Calling this method will force the bean to be written to the database and participate fully in the commit cycle e.g. pre-update rules will be run, etc.
